{{Infobox person | name = Arthur Keppel-Jones | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1909 | birth_place = | death_date = 1996 | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | alma mater = | employer = | occupation = Academic | title = | salary = | networth = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = }} '''Arthur Keppel-Jones''' (1909-1996) was a South African-born, Canadian-based historian and [[science fiction]] writer.<ref name="jeevesarthurkeppel">{{cite journal|last1=Jeeves|first1=Alan H.|title=Arthur Keppel-Jones: Scholar, Teacher, and Liberal Intellectual|journal=South African Historical Journal|date=May 1995|volume=32|pages=24–33}}</ref><ref name="encyclopediakeppeljones">{{cite web|title=Keppel-Jones, Arthur|url=http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/keppel-jones_arthur|website=[[The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018|date=April 30, 2017}}</ref> He was a senior lecturer at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] until he emigrated to Canada.<ref name="visser63">{{cite book|editor-first1=Pauline|editor-last1=Fletcher |last1=Visser|first1=Nicholas|title=Black/White Writing: Essays on South African Literature|chapter = The Politics of Future Projection in South African Fiction|date=1993|publisher=Bucknell University Press|location=Lewisburg, Pennsylvania|isbn=9780838752623|oclc=26502102|pages=63–64|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4SYiDRqyIeAC&pg=PA63&dq=Arthur+Keppel-Jones&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjl0r61g6jZAhUDOsAKHUxDAgMQ6AEIRTAF#v=onepage&q=Arthur%20Keppel-Jones&f=false}}</ref>
