'''Class Struggle''' is a board game for two to six players, designed by [[Bertell Ollman]]. It was published in 1978 by [[Avalon Hill]]. The game was intended to teach players about the politics of [[Marxism]], and was loosely compared the board game, [[Monopoly (game)|Monopoly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/1510/class-struggle|title=Class Struggle|website=BoardGameGeek|access-date=2017-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13217762/class_struggle_game_shows_real/|title="Class Struggle" game shows real system, Marxist prof says (1978)|date=1978-05-24|work=The Eagle|access-date=2017-08-20|pages=39}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13217777/of_professors_politicians_presidents/|title=Of professors, politicians, presidents (Class Struggle board game mention) (1981)|date=1981-06-07|work=The Salina Journal|access-date=2017-08-20|pages=4}}</ref> The game pits Workers against Capitalists, represented by hammers and top hats respectively.<ref name=":0" /> Players receive their class by a roll of the "genetic" dice. Players move around a board following dice rolls and draw "Chance" cards which either advantage or disadvantage them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16249323/class_struggle_latest_game/|title='Class Struggle' latest game|date=1978-05-25|work=Colorado Springs Gazette-Telegraph|access-date=2018-01-04|pages=49}}</ref> 

Critics of the game considered it to be "subversive" and lobbied some stores to remove the product from their shelves, largely unsuccessfully.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/13217806/board_game_purged_class_struggle/|title=Board game purged (Class Struggle) (1979)|date=1979-12-14|work=The Ottawa Journal|access-date=2017-08-20|pages=14}}</ref> In the year of its release, Bertell Ollman was interviewed about the game by print and TV news journalists.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16249481/nbc_tomorrow_game_creators_bruce/|title=(NBC) Tomorrow - game creators Bruce Spitz and Bertell Ollman (1978)|date=1978-11-20|work=The Gettysburg Times|access-date=2018-01-04|pages=14}}</ref> In 2014, Keith Plocek wrote that the objectives of the game were to "avoid [[Nuclear warfare|nuclear war]] and win the [[revolution]]". After attracting mainstream media attention during the Cold War, the game went on to sell approximately 230,000 copies. Plocek claims that the game "disappeared" in 1994.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/58318/story-class-struggle-americas-most-popular-marxist-board-game|title=The Story of ''Class Struggle'', America's Most Popular Marxist Board Game|date=2014-08-12|access-date=2017-08-20|language=en}}</ref> A Reddit post circa 2013 piqued limited renewed interest in the game among socialists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/socialism/comments/1s9q2y/i_found_this_at_a_garage_sale_thought_rsocialism/?sort=old|title=I found this at a Garage Sale, thought r/socialism would appreciate it. Class Struggle - The Board Game. • r/socialism|website=reddit|language=en|access-date=2017-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.critical-theory.com/class-struggle-board-game-greatest-exist/|title={{!}} Class Struggle the Board Game – The Greatest Thing to Ever ExistCritical-Theory.com|date=2013-12-09|work=Critical-Theory|access-date=2017-08-20|language=en-US}}</ref>

