'''Fritsche''' ('''Friedrich''') '''Closener''' (died before 11 March 1373) was a priest and historian of [[Strasbourg]]. His work was one of the first vernacular city chronicles, a type that became very common in [[Kingdom of Germany|Germany]] in the century that followed.{{sfn|Hegel|1876}}

Fritsche's father was Sifrid, a burger of Strasbourg, and his mother was Margareta Spirer. From 1343 Fritsche was the custodian of the ''Marienaltar'' in [[Strasbourg Cathedral]], where later he served as vicar of the large choir. In 1358 he received the prestigiuos [[prebend]] of Saint Catherine's Chapel.{{sfn|Gerber|1957}}

His most famous work is his ''Chronicle'',{{efn|''Kronika aller der bebeste und aller der romeschen keisere, die sit Cristus gebürte sint gewesen''{{sfn|Gerber|1957}}}} written in [[High German]] and connecting the history of his city, its region and its bishops with the wider world of the [[Holy Roman Empire|Empire]]. He says that he finished this work on 8 July 1362, the same day an earthquake struck Strasbourg.{{sfn|Hegel|1876}} His sources included [[Martin von Troppau]], a version of the ''[[Sächsische Weltchronik]]'' and the ''Bellum Waltherianum'' of his predecessor, [[Ellenhard|Ellenhard of Strasbourg]], which he translated and incorporated.{{sfn|Gerber|1957}}

Fritsche also compiled a German–Latin dictionary, the ''Vocabularium seu nomenclator'', and a now lost order of worship for Strasbourg Cathedral around 1364, ''Directorium chori''.{{sfn|Gerber|1957}}

