'''Jože Dežman''' (born 26 September 1955) is a [[Slovenia]]n historian, museum curator, philosopher and editor. He served as the director of the [[National Museum of Contemporary History]] in [[Ljubljana]].<ref>[http://www.muzej-nz.si/eng/eng_o_muzeju.html The National Museum of Contemporary History-Slovenia]</ref> Since March 2012, he has been the director of the [[Archives of Slovenia]], where he had replaced [[Dragan Matić]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/na-celu-arhiva-matica-zamenjal-dezman/278983 |title=Na čelu Arhiva Matića zamenjal Dežman |language=Slovenian |trans-title=Matić Replaced by Dežman as the Head of the Archives |date=15 March 2012 |newspaper=MMC RTV Slovenija}}</ref> Matić characterised the replacement as politically motivated and pointed out that Dežman is not an [[archivist]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rtvslo.si/slovenija/nekdanji-direktor-arhiva-moja-zamenjava-je-bila-politicna/279480 |title=Nekdanji direktor arhiva: Moja zamenjava je bila politična |language=Slovenian |trans-title=The Former Director of the Archives: My Replacement Was Political |newspaper=MMC RTV Slovenija |date=22 March 2012}}</ref>
Dežman was born in the [[Upper Carniola]]n town of [[Lesce]]. He studied history and philosophy at the [[University of Ljubljana]] and finished his studies in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gorenjci.si/Default.aspx?id=161 |title=DEŽMAN Jože |author=City Library of Kranj |work=Gorenjci.si}}</ref> For twenty years, he actively participated in the [[League of Communists of Slovenia]] and other Communist political organisations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnevnik.si/novice/slovenija/1042517400 |title=Spletni portret: Jože Dežman, zgodovinar, čigar stric je bil poveljnik gorenjske Udbe |language=Slovenian |trans-title=Web Portrait: Jože Dežman, a Historian Whose Uncle Was the Commander of the Upper Carniolan UDBA |date=19 March 2012 |newspaper=Dnevnik.si}}</ref> In the 1990s, he was an active member of the liberal party [[Liberal Democracy of Slovenia]]. He later turned to more conservative positions. Since the mid-2000s, he has advocated the inclusion of [[anti-Communist]] perspectives in [[History of Slovenia|Slovenian historiography]].{{citation needed|date=February 2012}}
Dežman described the fundamental characteristics of the crimes following the Second World War as follows:<ref>Joze Dezman, Communist Repression and Transitional Justice in Slovenia, in Peter Jambrek (ed.) Slovenian Presidency of the Council of the [[EUROPEAN UNION]], BRUXELLES, Ljubljana, 2008. At p. 204.</ref><ref>[http://internationallawobserver.eu/2009/06/22/responding-to-post-second-world-war-totalitarian-crimes-in-slovenia/ International Law Observer] Responding to post-Second World War totalitarian crimes in Slovenia Posted on June 22, 2009 by Jernej Letnar Cernic</ref>
{{Quotation|Killing civilians and prisoners of war after the Second World War is the greatest massacre of unarmed people of all times in Slovenian territory. Compared to Europe, the Yugoslav communist massacres after the Second World War are probably right after Stalinist purges and the [[Holodomor|Great Famine]] in the Ukraine. The number of those killed in Slovenia in the spring of 1945 can now be estimated at more than 100,000, Slovenia was the biggest post-War killing site in Europe. It was a mixture of events, when in Slovenia there are retreating German units, collaborator units, units of the Independent State of Croatia, Chetniks and Balkan civilians; more than 15,000 Slovenian inhabitants were murdered as well. Because of its brevity, number of casualties, way of execution and massiveness, it is an event that can be compared to the greatest crimes of communism and National Socialism.<ref>[http://www.mp.gov.si/fileadmin/mp.gov.si/pageuploads/2005/PDF/publikacije/Crimes_committed_by_Totalitarian_Regimes.pdf European Public Hearing on "Crimes Committed by Totalitarian Regimes”] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117160751/http://www.mp.gov.si/fileadmin/mp.gov.si/pageuploads/2005/PDF/publikacije/Crimes_committed_by_Totalitarian_Regimes.pdf |date=2012-01-17 }} Slovenian Presidency of the Council of the European Union (January–June 2008) and the European Commission, p. 204.</ref>}}
Dežman was the first chairman of the [[Commission on Concealed Mass Graves in Slovenia]]. He contributed to the European Public Hearing on [[European Public Hearing on “Crimes Committed by Totalitarian Regimes"|"Crimes Committed by Totalitarian Regimes"]] organized by Slovenian Presidency of the Council of the [[European Union]] (January–June 2008) and the [[European Commission]] by writing the chapter "Communist Repression and Transitional Justice in Slovenia" for the report.<ref>[http://www.mp.gov.si/fileadmin/mp.gov.si/pageuploads/2005/PDF/publikacije/Crimes_committed_by_Totalitarian_Regimes.pdf European Public Hearing on "Crimes Committed by Totalitarian Regimes”] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117160751/http://www.mp.gov.si/fileadmin/mp.gov.si/pageuploads/2005/PDF/publikacije/Crimes_committed_by_Totalitarian_Regimes.pdf |date=2012-01-17 }} Slovenian Presidency of the Council of the European Union (January–June 2008) and the European Commission, pp. 197–205.</ref>
